Plot

The plot() function is used to draw points (markers) in a diagram.

plot(c(1,2,4,8), c(3,5,8,10))

Sequence of points

plot(1:10)

Drawing a line

plot(1:10, type="l")

Plot Labels

The plot() function also accept other parameters, such as main, xlab and ylab.

plot(1:10, main="My Graph", xlab="The x-axis", ylab="The y axis")

Pie Chart

A pie chart is a circular graphical view of data.

# Create a vector of pies
x <- c(10,20,30,40)

# Display the pie chart
pie(x)

Bar plot

A bar chart uses rectangular bars to visualize data. Bar charts can be displayed horizontally or vertically. The height or length of the bars are proportional to the values they represent.

# x-axis values
x <- c("A", "B", "C", "D")

# y-axis values
y <- c(2, 4, 6, 8)

barplot(y, names.arg = x)

Histogram

Histograms can be created using the hist() function in R programming language. This function takes in a vector of values for which the histogram is plotted.

require(data.table)
mt <- fread("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/selva86/datasets/master/mtcars.csv")
hist(mt$wt)

GGPlot

library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.3.3
data("midwest", package = "ggplot2")  # load the data

Scatter plot

ggplot(midwest, aes(x=area, y=poptotal)) + geom_point()

g <- ggplot(midwest, aes(x=area, y=poptotal)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm")  # set se=FALSE to turnoff confidence bands

g1 <- g + coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,0.1), ylim=c(0, 1000000))  # zooms in

# Add Title and Labels
g1 + labs(title="Area Vs Population", subtitle="From midwest dataset", y="Population", x="Area", caption="Midwest Demographics")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# or

g1 + ggtitle("Area Vs Population", subtitle="From midwest dataset") + xlab("Area") + ylab("Population")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
